Recita testimonium] The evidence of Lucceius was a deposi ion taken down in writing and given on oath (ipsius jurati). It is not said why he was not present. But it seems that he was in Sardinia: ‘⁴ Lucceium convenire non potueram, quod abfuerat. Videre autem volebam, quod eram postridie Roma exiturus et quod ine in Sardiniam iter habebat.—Erat autem iturus, ut aiebat,

a. d. 111 Id. Apr. ut aut Labrone aut Pisis conscenderet '’ (Ad Q. Fr. ii. 6). This letter was written B.c. 56 (consul est czregius Lentulus), the same year in which this speech was delivered.

Drumann (Geschichte Rotns ii. 377) has a note on the year in which this speech was delivered: “Caelius was also tried in Rc. 54 before a praetor (Cn.) Domitius (Aheno- barbus) (Ad Q. Fr. ii. 13) and both Manu- tius in his note on this passage and Pighius confound these two trials. They assume that Cicero delivered this speech for Caelius in B.c. 54. But the evidence is that he deli- vered it in B.c. 56, while M. Crassus was still in Rome, a few days after the acquittal of Sex. Clodius (Pro Caelio, c. 32 3 Ad Q. Fr. ii. 6), consequently in the consulship of Lentulus Marcellinus and Philippus.'’ This being 50, the absence of Lucceius is ex- plained, and we have in his voyage to Sar- dinia an additional proof that this speech was delivered in B.c. 56.
